Contagious children's disease hits areas of the Wasatch Front
---------------------------------------------------
Several areas in Utah are seeing one of the biggest outbreaks of a contagious children's disease some people have ever seen. It's called hand, foot, and mouth disease, and it can make your kids feel downright miserable. [The Wasatch Range is a mountain range that stretches approximately 160 miles (260 km) from the Utah-Idaho border, south through central Utah. - Mod.CP]

"This is the first year in many years that I've seen it like it is, the way it has shown up this year. I've never seen it in the numbers like I've seen this year," said Luann Nunez at Luann's Daycare. Doctor Huff at the Intermountain hospital in Riverton said it's the time of year this thing goes around. "If you have a child who has it, and they go to daycare or a baby sitter and they spread it, and then a lot of the kids are going to get it," said Glen Huff, Pediatric Hospitalist, Riverton Hospital.

Huff said it's not a severe disease, but your kids will hate it. "The sores hurt really bad, and the kids just don't want to eat with them," said Huff.

So what do you do to keep your kids from getting it? Doctors Huff said make sure your kids wash their hands, and stay away from other kids who have it for about a week.

[Byline: Brian CarlsonImages]

