[Kuching is the capital and most populous city of the East Malaysian state of Sarawak. The HealthMap interactive map of Sarawak can be accessed at : http://healthmap.org/r/1mSG. - Mod.CP]


[Hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) is a common, mild disease usually caused by an enterovirus such as human coxsackievirus A , human coxsackievirus B or human enterovirus 71. Infection by human enterovirus 71 may have more serious outcomes, but other wise HFMD is a mild illness.

HFMD gets its name from the non-itchy rash that develops on the palms of your hands and soles of feet. It can also cause ulcers in the mouth although many individuals have no symptoms. It is generally believed that large outbreaks of hand, foot, and mouth disease do not occur in developed countries, but the above report from Utah contradicts this belief. Many countries in East and South-east Asia experience very large annual outbreaks affecting many thousands of children. A few children, and rarely adults, may have severe illnesses.

HFMD is spread from person to person through nose and throat secretions (such as saliva, sputum, or nasal mucus), blister fluid, or faeces of infected persons. The risk of being infected can be reduced by: washing hands often with soap and water, disinfecting dirty surfaces and soiled items, and avoiding close contact or sharing eating utensils with infected persons.

ProMED-mail receives very many reports of HFMD at this time of year and no more than a few can be posted. The above three are posted solely as examples. There are no specific treatments and unfortunately the infectious agent is rarely identified, consequently the prospects for development of preventive vaccines, except perhaps in the case of enterovirus 71, are poor. - Mod.CP.


A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1jtA.]
